# CCS Core Platform — Cursor Workspace Rules

Permanent development rules for AI-assisted work on Crazy Carrot Studios repositories.

**Applies to:** `ccs-framework` (this upstream repo) and future game repos such as `ccs-survival`.

---

## Repository roles

### ccs-framework (reusable upstream core)

- Reusable upstream Core Platform — reusable forever
- Runtime systems, bootstrap, modules, services, diagnostics, validation
- **No** gameplay systems
- **No** survival mechanics
- **No** western-specific logic
- **No** MMO content
- **No** game-specific UI
- **No** faction or story systems

All gameplay code belongs in a **game repository**, not here.

### ccs-survival (gameplay repository)

- Actual survival-focused gameplay and game content
- Survival mechanics, crafting, factions, quests, weapons, lore
- Western MMO and other survival genres **inside this repo** (product/theme), not in framework naming
- Modules under `Assets/CCS/Modules/` in the game project

---

## Core architecture policies

### Never introduce

- Singleton managers or static global service locators
- Auto-discovery systems (reflection scanning, scene-wide discovery)
- Scene scanning for installers or modules
- `FindObjectOfType` / `FindObjectsOfType` architecture for composition
- Hardcoded gameplay assumptions in Core
- Direct scene dependencies in platform code
- Gameplay logic inside `Assets/CCS/Framework/Core/`

### Prefer

- Module architecture (`CCS_IModule`, `CCS_ModuleInstallerBase`, manual install plans)
- Explicit registration (bootstrap installers, services, updatables)
- Service-driven systems (`CCS_ServiceRegistry`)
- Lifecycle-managed systems (`CCS_ModuleLifecycleState`, `CCS_Result`)
- Instance ownership via `CCS_RuntimeHost` (no singleton)
- Multiplayer-safe patterns: deterministic ownership, no hidden global state
- Reusable systems that any future CCS game can adopt

---

## CCS script standards

When creating or editing C# in this ecosystem:

- Use the **CCS file header** format (script name, category, purpose, placement, author, date, notes)
- Follow **region order** conventions (see `Assets/CCS/Framework/Documentation/CCS_Script_Standards.md`)
- Use **descriptive naming** (`CCS_` prefix for framework types; PascalCase/camelCase per standards)
- **No XML doc summaries** on types — use header comments for behavior documentation
- **Tooltips** on `[SerializeField]` private fields exposed in the Inspector
- **Runtime vs Editor** separation — no `UnityEditor` in runtime assemblies
- **Event-driven** communication via `CCS_EventDispatcher` where decoupling is appropriate
- Use `CCS_Logger` for categorized logging; use `CCS_Result` / `CCS_CoreErrorCode` for operation outcomes

---

## Repository naming rules

### Use

| Name | Role |
|------|------|
| `ccs-framework` | Reusable upstream core platform |
| `ccs-survival` | Survival-focused gameplay repo |

### Do not use

- `ccs-reckoning-survival` or other **game-title** names for reusable architecture docs or repo slugs
- Game-specific repo naming for framework/upstream guidance

### Reckoning and product lore

- **Reckoning**, western MMO, factions, and narrative are **lore/product/game title** — valid inside `ccs-survival` (scenes, content, marketing)
- **Not** framework branding, upstream repo names, or Core module IDs in `ccs-framework`

Example module IDs in game repos: `ccs.survival.inventory` — not `ccs.reckoning.*` in shared upstream docs.

---

## Module policies

| Location | Policy |
|----------|--------|
| **Core modules** (`ccs-framework` / `Framework/Core/`) | Reusable only; no gameplay assumptions; smoke tests isolated under `SmokeTests/` |
| **Gameplay modules** | Belong in **ccs-survival** (or other `ccs-<genre>` game repos) under `Assets/CCS/Modules/` |

- Manual registration only — no auto-install from dependency metadata
- Dependency metadata is preflight validation only

---

## Future multiplayer direction

Design for long-term MMO/survival scale **without** implementing networking everywhere prematurely:

- **Multiplayer-safe:** avoid static global state; prefer instance-owned subsystems
- **Authority-safe:** clear ownership of registries and hosts per runtime context
- **Modular:** features as modules with explicit install order
- **Deterministic** where practical for simulation and validation
- **Scalable** for future co-op / MMO survival — contracts first, netcode in game repos later

